# FIRMS MODIS and VIIRS Active-Fire Fields

This folder contains FIRMS active-fire detections downloaded over the full Mace Head HYSPLIT trajectory domain for 2003–2025.

FIRMS data access requires a NASA FIRMS map key. Request your own key here:

https://firms.modaps.eosdis.nasa.gov/api/map_key/

Each row represents one satellite-detected thermal anomaly or active-fire pixel. The reported latitude and longitude are the centre of the flagged satellite pixel, not the physical fire perimeter.

MODIS active-fire pixels are approximately 1 km at nadir. VIIRS active-fire pixels are approximately 375 m at nadir. Pixel size increases away from nadir, so `scan` and `track` must be retained when interpreting footprint size, spatial uncertainty, or proximity to HYSPLIT trajectories.

NASA describes FIRMS detections as active fires or other thermal anomalies, including vegetation fires, volcanoes, static land sources, and offshore sources.

## Products

The dataset may include detections from:

- MODIS active-fire products
- VIIRS active-fire products

MODIS and VIIRS fields are similar but not fully interchangeable. Brightness temperatures, confidence coding, spatial resolution, and detection sensitivity differ between sensors. Do not pool sensor-specific thermal metrics without explicitly accounting for product differences.

## Key columns

| Column | Meaning | Units or coding | Scientific interpretation |
|---|---|---:|---|
| `brightness` | MODIS channel 21/22 brightness temperature or VIIRS I4 brightness temperature, depending on product | K | Mid-infrared thermal intensity of the detected pixel. Larger values indicate a stronger sub-pixel thermal anomaly, but values are sensor-dependent and should not be compared directly between MODIS and VIIRS without caution. |
| `scan` | Across-track pixel size | km | Width of the satellite pixel footprint. Larger values indicate a larger ground footprint and greater spatial uncertainty. Useful for trajectory proximity filtering or footprint weighting. |
| `track` | Along-track pixel size | km | Length of the satellite pixel footprint. Together with `scan`, gives an approximate pixel area. |
| `acq_date` | Satellite acquisition date | UTC date | Date of satellite overpass. Combine with `acq_time` to construct a proper UTC timestamp. |
| `acq_time` | Satellite acquisition time | UTC, HHMM integer | Time of overpass. Values must be padded to four digits before parsing, for example `40` becomes `0040` and `502` becomes `0502`. |
| `confidence` | Detection confidence | MODIS: 0–100 percent; VIIRS: `l`, `n`, `h` | Quality indicator for each detected pixel. MODIS confidence is numeric, whereas VIIRS confidence is categorical. |
| `version` | Processing collection and source | Text or number | Identifies product collection and processing stream. Standard processing is preferable for retrospective analysis. Near-real-time products are useful operationally but may be revised. |
| `bright_t31` | MODIS channel 31 or VIIRS I5 brightness temperature | K | Longwave infrared background or fire-pixel temperature. Useful with `brightness` to evaluate thermal contrast and contextual anomaly strength. |
| `frp` | Fire radiative power | MW | Pixel-integrated radiative power. This is the most useful continuous proxy for combustion intensity and emissions potential, although it is affected by cloud, viewing geometry, saturation, and sub-pixel fire structure. |
| `type` | Inferred hotspot type | 0, 1, 2, 3 | For MODIS/FIRMS: `0 = presumed vegetation fire`, `1 = active volcano`, `2 = other static land source`, `3 = offshore`. For biomass-burning aerosol interpretation, usually retain `type == 0`; treat `type == 2` and `type == 3` separately or remove them. |

Approximate pixel area can be calculated as:

```python
fires["pixel_area_km2"] = fires["scan"] * fires["track"]
